Conceptual Questions

1.

a.

I do not think Shourya has a reliable measure of physical health. He is

using self-report questionnaires to measure physical health. It is not a

standardized or objectional measure of health such as physical assessments.

He also only has a sample of 5, and is not taking into account physical

health data prior to watching the vidoes. It is unlikely that a

participants physical health would change after watching a Youtube video.

b.

The first type of validity is external validity; the extent to which we can

generalize the findings from our study to the population. In Shouryas

study, external validity is not satisfactory. His sample is small and

homogenous (5 college students). Because of this, the findings may not

represent the larger population. Additionally, Shourya manipulated

depression by showing participants either a comedy or tragic video. This

may not generalize to individualls with diagnosed clinical depression. The

second type of validity is conclusion validity; the extent to which the

study allows us to detect an effect if an effect exists in the population.

Shouryas study is not satisfactory in conclusion validity due to the lack

of random assignment. The participants self-selected themselves into

groups, so it might be an uneven distribution. He also failed to control

confounding variables that may have an effect on physical health. The third

type of validity is internal validity; the extent to which the study allows

us to draw causal conclusions about the effect of the predictor variable on

the outcome variable. Shouryas study is not satisfactory in internal

validity due to lack of random assignment, the test-retest method, and the

lack of explaining confounding variables. In a test-retest study,

participants scores tend to be closer to the mean the second time around.

The fourth type of validity is construct validity; the extent to which an

indicator measures what it was intended to measure. Shouryas study is not

satisfactory in construct validity due to the control groups. Watching a

sad or happy video may induce an emotional reaction, but does not directly

represent depression.

c.

One change Shourya could make in his study is to icnrease the sample size

and use random assignment. This change would increase external validity

because having a larger sample makes it more likely you will be able to

generalize your findings to the larger population. This change would also

increase conclusion validity because any differences in outcomes between

groups can be more confidently attributed to the independent variable,

rather than alternative explanations. Another change Shourya could make in

his study is to have both self-report questionnaires and physical

assessments to measure physical health. This change would make the measure

of physical health more reliable, therefore increasing construct validity.

2.

a.

Erin is 22 years old. z=(score - mean) / (standard deviation) ->

1 = (score - 20.5)/1.5 -> 1.5 = score - 20.5 -> score = 22.

b.

The sum of squared errors is the standard error in relation to a sampling

distribution.

c.

A z-distribution is used when you know the population standard deviation.

A t-distribution is used when you only know the sample standard deviation.

3.

a.

Two alternatice ways to aggregate separate error values into a summary

measure of total error are sum or errors (SE) and sum of absoulte errors

(SAE).

b.

Sum of absolute error (SAE) would be minimized if we used the sample median

instead of the sample mean as our parameter estimate for b0.

c.

Mean squared error (MSE) is the remaining error per remaining potential

parameter. In the basic/mean-only model the MSE is also known as the

variance.

4.

a.

np2 = SSEc-SSEa / SSEc -> np2 = (1000 - 750) / 1000 -> np2 = 0.25. This

value is the proportion of variance explained. In this example, partial eta

squared means that 25% of variance in Y is explaind by X.

b.

Mean-centering the predictor would not change our parameter estimate for

b1.

c.

F = ((SSEc-SSEa) / (Pa-Pc)) / (SSEa / (N-Pa)) ->

F = ((1000-750)/(2-1))/(750/(27-2)) -> F = 250/30 -> F(1, 25)=83.33.

d.

The numerator of the F statistic represents the average SSE reduction from

the compact to the augmented model, per each parameter added to the

augmented model that was not in the compact model.The denominator of the F-

statistic represents the variance unexplained by the augmented model.

5.

DF=N-P -> DF=100-2 -> DF=98 -> tcrit = 1.984

CI = b1 +/- (tcrit * SE) -> CI = 0.78 +/- (1.984 * 0.28) ->

CI upper = 1.296 & CI lower = 0.264

This CI means that Sara can be confident that 95% of times, her estimate of

mood swings will fall between 0.264 and 1.296.

e.

The reliability of the agreeableness and imagination scales in our sample

is moderately high. A higher reliability is typically more desirable

because it shows that your study is measuring what you intended to measure.

A Crohnbachs alpha score can range from 0 to 1. Scores equal to or above

are considered acceptable. A researcher can never reach a perfect alpha

score of 1 due to human and measurement error. In addition, trying to

reliability can have some tradeoffs. For example, having a longer

questionairre would increase reliability, but would bore the participant

and would require more resources.

d3 <- d2 %>%

12.

a.

In this study, we examined how cognitive ability in adolescence relates to

imagination and how receiving supportive parenting in adolescence

influences agreeableness. We collected data from 3,093 participants. We ran

a linear regression in which we regressed imagination on cognitive ability.

As hypothesized, the effect of cognitive ability was statistically

significant, F(1, 156.7) = 2231, p < .005, np^2 = 0.07. We also ran a

linear regression in which we regressed agreeableness on supportive

parenting. As hypothesized, the effect of supportive parenting was

statistically significant, F(1, 2209) = 9.01, p = .003, np^2 = 4.06e-03.

F(1, 793) = 3.71, p = .054 The effect of supportive parenting on

agreeableness differs across families with divorced vs married parents.
